The paper deals with complexity classes and their hierarchies, which are typically studied in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of Boolean closures and symmetric difference hierarchies suggests a connection to logic and set theory, which are also relevant to the study of computational complexity (cs.LO). The mention of sparse sets and the low hierarchy suggests a connection to computational complexity and algorithms (cs.DS), while the use of promise hierarchies suggests a connection to cryptography and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the mention of the Hausdorff hierarchy suggests a connection to topology and discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
